<!--- The ARDS AND PRONE -->
<section id="PronePositionAndArds" class="pb-0 pb-5">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-lg-10 col-xl-8">
                <div class="d-flex justify-content-between align-items-center mb-3">


                </div>
                <h1>Treating ARDS and Covid-19</h1>

            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>
<section class="p-0" data-reading-position>
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center position-relative">
            <div class="col-lg-10 col-xl-8">
                <div class="rounded o-hidden">
                    <div class="plyr" data-plyr-provider="youtube" data-plyr-embed-id="wY2X9roWtHA"></div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-xl-7 col-lg-8 col-md-10">
                <article class="article">
                    <p class="lead">
                        Treating ARDS is difficult. In 2018 a strong recommendation was added, imploring higher use of the prone position (face down) , following a study showing up to 50% lower mortality.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        <h4>What does the science say?</h4>
                        <blockquote class="bg-primary-alt">

                            <div class="h3 mb-2">“Prone positioning is currently a recommendation to treat ARDS patients, and is associated with a 50% decrease in mortality following intubation.”</div>
                            <span class="text-small text-muted"><a href="https://pulmccm.org/ards-review/prone-positioning-ards-ats-sccm/">Source : PulmCcm.org</a></span>
                            <a href="#" class="btn btn-primary btn-sm">
                                <img class="icon" src="assets/img/icons/social/twitter.svg" alt="twitter social icon" data-inject-svg />
                                <span>Tweet</span>
                            </a>
                        </blockquote>

                        See this excerpt from PulmCcm.org:
                        <blockquote>
                            <div class="mb-2">
                                Prone positioning improves ventilation-perfusion matching (transferring delivered oxygen into the bloodstream more efficiently) and keeps alveolar units open and evenly distributed at end-expiration (improving gas exchange and preventing ventilator-induced lung injury). Through one or more of these mechanisms,<strong> prone positioning is believed to improve survival for some patients with ARDS.</strong>

                            </div>
                            <span class="text-small text-muted"><a href="https://pulmccm.org/ards-review/prone-positioning-ards-ats-sccm/">Source : PulmCcm.org</a></span>
                            <a href="#" class="btn btn-primary btn-sm">
                                <img class="icon" src="assets/img/icons/social/twitter.svg" alt="twitter social icon" data-inject-svg />
                                <span>Tweet</span>
                            </a>

                        </blockquote>
                    </p>
                    <p>The recommendation to use the Swimmers Position was the result of a high quality study.</p>
                    <blockquote>
                        <div class="mb-2">
                            In making their recommendation, the guideline authors relied on the PROSEVA study, which found a <strong>somewhat incredible 50% reduction in death from ARDS (16% vs 33%)</strong>, and post hoc analyses of previous ARDS trials testing prone positioning.

                        </div>
                        <span class="text-small text-muted"><a href="https://pulmccm.org/ards-review/prone-positioning-ards-ats-sccm/">Source : PulmCcm.org</a></span>
                        <a href="#" class="btn btn-primary btn-sm">
                            <img class="icon" src="assets/img/icons/social/twitter.svg" alt="twitter social icon" data-inject-svg />
                            <span>Tweet</span>
                        </a>

                    </blockquote>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        This is due to how prone position is a more natural state of the lung, and allows higher rate of fluid clearance from lungs, because the orientation of the lungs allows the fluid to collect ventrally, and is assisted by gravity and reabsorbed into the tissue. This is a more natural way to obtain the same effect as high PEEP, and in combination the effects are even better.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        However a little further down, we also read :
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <blockquote>
                            <div class="mb-2">
                                There’s a <strong>natural resistance to prone positioning for patients in ARDS among physicians, nurses, and administrators. </strong>Moving severely hypoxemic, ventilator dependent patients is inherently risky. Studies testing prone positioning showed an increased incidence of endotracheal tube obstruction among those proned. Pressure sores were also increased. In one study, arrhythmias or hypotension, vomiting, lost IV access, and endotracheal tube displacement were all significantly more likely in proned patients.
                                The PROSEVA study was conducted at French centers with several years’ prior experience in prone positioning for patients with ARDS. <strong>Less-experienced centers would be correct to ignore the low observed complication rate in PROSEVA, and to use extreme caution with each patient.</strong>

                            </div>
                            <span class="text-small text-muted"><a href="https://pulmccm.org/ards-review/prone-positioning-ards-ats-sccm/">Source : PulmCcm.org</a></span>
                            <a href="#" class="btn btn-primary btn-sm">
                                <img class="icon" src="assets/img/icons/social/twitter.svg" alt="twitter social icon" data-inject-svg />
                                <span>Tweet</span>
                            </a>

                        </blockquote>


                    </p>
                    <h4>Swimmers position</h4>

                    <p>
                        Prone position is effective in treating ARDS, and is realized through the so called "Swimmers position". The patient is positioned in a normal hospital bed, face down with improvised supports for torost and head, using available duveys and blankets.
                    </p>
                    <figure>
                        <img src="img/swimmers-position.jpg" alt="Image" class="rounded">
                        <figcaption>Swimmers position</figcaption>
                    </figure>

                    However, obese patient are likely to put pressure on the abdomen, which reduces the effiacy of prone postion. It is this insight that has prompted us to engage in improved positioning for ARDS.
                    <blockquote>
                        <div class="mb-2">
                            Studies have shown that prone positioning causes a decrease in cardiac output. Contributing to this is a reduction in venous return, effects on arterial filling and decreased left ventricular compliance due to higher intra-thoracic pressures. Again, any pressure on the abdomen can accentuate this by compressing the IVC and decreasing venous return.
                        </div>
                        <span class="text-small text-muted"><a href="/Papers/Patient-positioning-during-anaesthesia.pdf">Source : Dr Jennifer Hartley, Canberra Hospital </a></span>
                        <a href="#" class="btn btn-primary btn-sm">
                            <img class="icon" src="assets/img/icons/social/twitter.svg" alt="twitter social icon" data-inject-svg />
                            <span>Tweet</span>
                        </a>

                    </blockquote>

                    <p>
                        Swimmers position is basically the best kind of prone position you can do in an ordinary hospital bed, without any specialized equipment supporting the prone and regulating pressure.
                        The success of the swimmers position depends entirely on the training, time and care provided by the nurses or physioteraphists responsible for the positioning and turning.
                        Also, as we will see in the next chapter - turning the patient in and out of prone position safely requires a large crew, takes more time than expected, and requires training.
                        All of which is in short supply in todays Intensive Care units.
                    </p>

                    <h5>Summary</h5>
                    <p>To summarize, our findings are</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Prone position is important in treating ARDS</li>
                        <li>Swimmers Position is not ideal, particularly given obese patients which weigh down their own abdomen, reducing the expansion of the lungs, counteracting the prone position</li>
                        <li>Swimmers position requires turning the patient</li>
                    </ul>
                    <h5>Sources</h5>
                    <ol>
                        <li><a href="/Papers/Patient-positioning-during-anaesthesia.pdf">Patient positioning during anesthesia, Dr. Jennifer Hartley Canberra Hospital</a></li>
                        <li><a href="/Papers/PRONE_Position–Basics–Anaesthesia-News.pdf">Prone Position Basics (Anaesthesia News) </a></li>
                        <li><a href="/Papers/SafeProneCheclist.pdf">Safe Prone Checklist, 2017 </a></li>
                        <li><a href="/Papers/PronePositionInARDS.pdf">Prone Position in ARDS, 2016 </a></li>
                    </ol>

                </article>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

