<section class="p-0" data-reading-position>
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center position-relative">
            <div class="col-lg-10 col-xl-8">
                <div class="rounded o-hidden">
                    <div class="plyr" data-plyr-provider="youtube" data-plyr-embed-id="Cwu8zMYppis"></div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-xl-7 col-lg-8 col-md-10">
                <article class="article">
                    <p class="lead">
                        Right now, several forces converge to produce an imminent and extreme shortage of trained medical personell. The profession where this is most pronounced are trained intensive care nurses. The expansion of intensive care happens at the same time as staff are sent into quarantine. Training new staff is one important solution, but reducing time needed for common tasks is another.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Our preliminary research interviewing hospital professionals indicate that the time required to turn a patient between prone and supine requires:
                        <ul>
                            <li>
                                Takes a total of about 25-35 minutes for the lead nurse.
                            </li>
                            <li>Takes about 15-20 minutes for all other nurses involved</li>
                            <li>Requires four to five nurses</li>
                            <li>Prone position between 12 to 15 hours</li>
                            <li>Some patients are more fragile, and must be turned more often</li>
                        </ul>
                    </p>
                    <figure>
                        <img src="images/safe-prone-maneuver.png" alt="Image" class="rounded">
                        <figcaption>Safe prone maneuver- Source <a href="/papers/SafeProneChecklist.pdf">Safe Prone Checklist</a></figcaption>
                    </figure>

                    <p>
                        Due to the number of nurses required, each turning takes approximately 1.5 man-hours of nurse time. At best, each patients requires only about two turnings per 25 hours.
                        This brings the total amount of nurse-time required to turn a patient with ARDS up to about 3. Turning patients comes in addition to
                        all the other work nurses does, such as :
                        <ul>
                            <li>Measuring blood pressure and oxygenation</li>
                            <li>Caring for patient, including pressure ulcers</li>
                            <li>Collecting information for doctors</li>
                            <li>Responding to emergency request for work</li>
                        </ul>

                        As intensive care units rapidly filling up with patients requiring the same type of work-intensive treatment, Intensive Care nurses are running form one case to the next.
                        In such an environment, reducing the workload and number of nurses required to turn patients can dramatically improve working condition and quality of service in an ICU unit, freeing up time
                        for other tasks.

                    </p>
                    <h4>Turning beds exist and are proven</h4>
                    <p>
                        Beds that assist in the turning of patients, based on a similar principle has been used for over 20 years. However, these are much to cumbersome for rapid production and deployment.
                        We are using the opportunity to develop turning beds that can be rapidly deployed and with minimal training,  based on proven usefulness.
                    </p>
                    <figure>
                        <img src="images/rotoprone-cumbersome-monster.jpeg" alt="Image" class="rounded">
                        <figcaption>RotoProne bed</figcaption>
                    </figure>
                    <p>
                        The rotating bed is not well known, but has a strong track record to be used in cases with ARDS. During the Swine Flu epidemic, rotating beds proved useful for allowing the prone position for nurses.
                    </p>
                    <blockquote class="bg-primary-alt">
                        <div class="h3 mb-2">Those who treated Dillon (a patient) believe the (turning) bed made the difference. Without it, she might have a become one of the hospital's first swine flu casualties. "She got the benefit from it within the first four hours, but it took eight days for her not to need it anymore"</div>
                        <span class="text-small text-muted"><a href="https://www.chron.com/news/houston-texas/article/Rotating-hospital-bed-aided-swine-flu-fight-1582900.php"> Source : www.chron.com</a><</span>
                        <a href="#" class="btn btn-primary btn-sm">
                            <img class="icon" src="assets/img/icons/social/twitter.svg" alt="twitter social icon" data-inject-svg />
                            <span>Tweet</span>
                        </a>
                    </blockquote>

                    <h5>Summary</h5>
                    <p>
                        From existing literature, existing products and physiological asessements, turning beds help turn the patient more often and with better room for abdomen to expand when intubated.
                        It is therfore likely, that turning beds can produce same or better results than "Swimmers Position" when treating ARDS.
                        Just as important in times of high demand for trained nurses, is the considerable reduction in nurse-time required to perform the turning maneuver.
                        Reducing the number of staff required can dramatically affect the availablility of nurse time for other tasks, and avoid turning maneuver tasks that clog up the
                        worflow in the Intensive Care unit.
                    </p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Turning beds have a proven track records</li>
                        <li>Reduces pressure on abdomen, a known problem with Swimmers Position</li>
                        <li>Making the turning maneuver quicker to perform</li>
                        <li>Requres less time to perform the maneuver</li>
                        <li>Reduces trained man-hours from more than 1.5h per turning maneuver to less than 45 min.</li>
                    </ul>


                    <h5>Sources</h5>
                    <ol>
                        <li><a href="https://www.jewellnursingsolutions.com/pressure-injury-prevention/">Myths About Turning And Repositioning, jewellnursingsolutions.com</a></li>

                    </ol>

                </article>
            </div>
        </div>
